{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17509749","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17509749"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T12:19:05+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T12:19:05+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11440"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"11440","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/11440"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.61,0.03,0.11,0.12,0.13]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4074"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"53303"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"4074","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/4074"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question","status":"accepted","createdAt":"2021-12-16T03:43:42+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-09-26T08:23:19+09:30","updatedAction":"commented","acceptedAt":"2022-06-03T15:51:35+09:30","editorNotifiedAt":null,"feedbackAt":"2025-09-28 08:58:56"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11440"}},"updatedBy":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"9"}},"author":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"9"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"38747"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"31"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"393"},{"type":"tags","id":"1284"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"4952"},{"type":"contributions","id":"6261"},{"type":"contributions","id":"15575"},{"type":"contributions","id":"36380"},{"type":"contributions","id":"49535"}]},"lastContribution":{"data":null},"lastRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"38747"}},"lastActivity":{"data":null},"lastFeedback":{"data":null}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"53303","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/53303"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 45-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic for follow-up after being recently diagnosed with metastatic melanoma. On her routine staging scan, several metastases were noted in deep cerebral and brainstem structures, with no significant surrounding oedema. She has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears well with vital signs within normal limits. A complete neurological examination reveals no abnormal neurological symptoms or signs. Plans for her ongoing management are discussed at a multidisciplinary team meeting.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate first-line therapy?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Ipilimumab plus nivolumab immunotherapy","Craniotomy and resection of metastases","Whole brain radiotherapy","Dacarbazine chemotherapy","Corticosteroids"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with multiple asymptomatic brain metastases from melanoma. In this scenario, the most appropriate first-line therapy is \u003Cstrong\u003Eipilimumab plus nivolumab immunotherapy\u003C/strong\u003E. These are immune checkpoint inhibitors that work synergistically to enhance the immune system\u0027s ability to fight cancer cells. Ipilimumab is a monoclonal antibody that blocks CTLA-4, while nivolumab blocks PD-1. Both CTLA-4 and PD-1 are inhibitory immune system signals, and blocking them stimulates the immune system to fight the cancer. This combination has shown significant efficacy in treating melanoma with brain metastases, especially in asymptomatic patients.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECraniotomy and resection\u003C/strong\u003E of metastases would be considered first-line therapy for patients with a solitary brain metastasis or if a single metastasis was causing significant symptoms of raised intracranial pressure or mass effect. However, this patient has multiple deep brain and brainstem metastases, which are generally inoperable, and she is asymptomatic.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EWhole brain radiotherapy\u003C/strong\u003E is typically considered a palliative measure for patients with multiple symptomatic brain metastases. It is not the first-line approach for asymptomatic patients, as it can cause significant cognitive side effects and may interfere with the efficacy of subsequent systemic therapies.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDacarbazine\u003C/strong\u003E is a chemotherapeutic agent that was previously used in melanoma treatment. However, its use has largely been superseded by more effective immunotherapies and targeted therapies, particularly in the context of brain metastases where its efficacy is limited.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECorticosteroids\u003C/strong\u003E are used as a palliative measure to reduce vasogenic oedema surrounding metastases. They are typically reserved for patients with symptomatic brain metastases as a possible bridge to definitive therapy. In this case, the patient is asymptomatic and there is no significant surrounding oedema, so corticosteroids are not indicated as first-line therapy.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe management of melanoma brain metastases has evolved significantly with the advent of effective systemic therapies. For asymptomatic patients with multiple brain metastases, as in this case, combination immunotherapy with ipilimumab and nivolumab has become the preferred first-line approach, offering the potential for durable disease control both intracranially and extracranially.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Systemic drug therapy is the most effective treatment for patients with multiple melanoma brain metastases and can be considered first-line treatment (as an alternative to local brain therapy) in asymptomatic patients, with multidisciplinary support from a radiation oncologist and a neurosurgeon.","Immune checkpoint inhibitors such as ipilimumab and nivolumab work by \u0027releasing the brake\u0027 on immune cells, facilitating immune-mediated clearance of tumour cells."],"references":["Hong AM, Waldstein C, Shivalingam B, Carlino MS, Atkinson V, Kefford RF, McArthur GA, Menzies AM, Thompson JF, Long GV. Management of melanoma brain metastases: Evidence-based clinical practice guidelines by Cancer Council Australia. Eur J Cancer. 2021 Jan;142:10-17. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/33207293/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"38747"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11440"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"38747","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/38747"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-09-18T12:15:39+09:30","updatedAt":"2024-09-18T12:17:19+09:30","number":9,"notes":"","plagiarismCheckedAt":"2024-09-18T12:16:38+09:30","plagiarismScore":16.8,"plagiarismReportUrl":"https://emedici-copyleaks.syd1.digitaloceanspaces.com/plagiarism-report-4074-9.pdf?X-Amz-Content-Sha256=UNSIGNED-PAYLOAD\u0026X-Amz-Algorithm=AWS4-HMAC-SHA256\u0026X-Amz-Credential=DO00QAKVE68N83EBLT2J%2F20250929%2Fsyd1%2Fs3%2Faws4_request\u0026X-Amz-Date=20250929T024906Z\u0026X-Amz-SignedHeaders=host\u0026X-Amz-Expires=601200\u0026X-Amz-Signature=01e22376f8660c3f7a4a73e308440e6dfd745c1050b001ff19570699f8d00792"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4074"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"53303"}},"author":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"12201"}},"generation":{"data":null}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"31","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/31"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udf97","name":"Oncology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position